  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because TJX is a mature business, it is highly sensitive to the discount rate. A 1% increase in the discount rate reduces the intrinsic value significantly.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>International Expansion:</strong> If TJX accelerates its successful rollout in Europe or Australia beyond expectations, top-line growth could exceed our 9% estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>HomeGoods Boom:</strong> The HomeGoods segment is highly discretionary but highly profitable. A sustained housing boom could supercharge this segment's margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Share Repurchases:</strong> TJX consistently buys back stock. Fewer shares outstanding in the future means each share is entitled to more of the cash flow, artificially boosting per-share value over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Supply Chain Snarls:</strong> The off-price model relies on fluid global supply chains to source inventory cheaply. Persistent shipping disruptions can squeeze margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumer Spending Cliff:</strong> While off-price retail is resilient, it is not immune to a deep, prolonged recession where consumers completely halt discretionary apparel and home spending.</li>
    <li><strong>Brand Deterioration:</strong> If premium brands tighten their inventory controls and stop selling excess stock to off-price retailers, TJX's "treasure hunt" appeal diminishes.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. During bubbles, P/E ratios are high; during panics, they're low. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. For a company with TJX's low beta and highly resilient business model, an 8.5% required return is appropriate for this relatively low-risk equity. The sensitivity table shows how values shift at 7.5% and 9.5%.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the "off-price" model affect this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The off-price model makes TJX's cash flows highly resilient. During economic booms, consumers buy more. During downturns, higher-income shoppers trade down to TJX. This stability justifies a lower discount rate and steady growth projections compared to standard mall retailers.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

